<h2>Blackbody Design</h2>

<p>The design and construction of an infrared calibration source,
although simple in principle, can be difficult to realise in practice,
especially when high radiometric accuracy is the primary
goal. Space-borne infrared radiometers, such as <a
href="../../hirdls/home.htm">HIRDLS</a>, routinely
employ in-flight calibration subsystems, comprising a <a
href="http://www.npl.co.uk/thermal/stuff/guide4.html">high emissivity
blackbody</a> target and supporting electronics. The ideal would be a
'perfectly black' (&#949 = 1) infrared source, but the design
constraints imposed on space instrumentation, such as mass, size and
power, inevitably lead to a compromise and an agreed error budget,
although a blackbody target with a normal emissivity greater than
0.999 should be possible with careful design. Factors affecting
blackbody emissivity include the geometry of the cavity and the
hemispherical spectral emissivity of the internal, 'viewed'
surfaces. Factors affecting the accuracy of the blackbody as an
infrared calibration source (in addition to emissivity) include the
temperature uniformity and stability of the cavity walls, and the
absolute accuracy and stability of the thermometers used to sense
temperatures.</p> <TABLE WIDTH=100% CELLPADDING="5%"><TR><TD
VALIGN=TOP>
<CENTER>
<a href="blackbodies/fig1_large.jpg"><IMG
SRC="blackbodies/fig1_small.jpg"></a><BR> <BR><I>Fig 1: View of
assembled IFCBB, aperture</I></TD>
</CENTER>
</TD><TD>
<CENTER>
<a href="blackbodies/fig2_large.jpg"><IMG
SRC="blackbodies/fig2_small.jpg"></a><BR> <BR><I>Fig 2: View of
assembled IFCBB, hand held</I></TD>
</CENTER>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<p>Frequently, the in-flight calibrator is used with a view to 'cold
space' to provide a two-point calibration of the radiance transfer
function. The HIRDLS in-flight calibration subsystem, which comprised
the In-Flight Calibration Blackbody (IFCBB) (Fig 1 and Fig 2) the
Blackbody Electronics Unit (BEU) (Fig 3) and the interconnecting
harness was supplied by Oxford University.  The BEU, a compact
flight-engineered a.c. resistance bridge, was a joint development
between Oxford University and <a
href="http://www.brightwell-instruments.co.uk/">Brightwell Instruments
LTD</a>.  The large, full-aperture calibration blackbodies used during
<a href="../facilities/2point2_metre_facility/targets_5.html">HIRDLS
radiometric calibration</a> were designed and integrated at Oxford,
Fig 4 and Fig 5. Blackbody emissivities were not measured directly,
but were calculated using 'in-house' software design tools and the
measured <a
href="http://www.npl.co.uk/measurement_services/ms_QD.html">Spectral
Hemispherical Reflectances</a> of the black paint used to coat the
cavity walls. The thermometers for both the IFCBB and the external
targets were selected, conditioned and calibrated at the department,
although the sensor type and manufacture were different for the
in-flight calibrator and ground-based targets. The IFCBB underwent <a
href="../facilities/thermometry.html">thermometric calibration</a> as a complete assembly, and after
the surface-mounted sensors had been conditioned by thermal
cycling. This was neither practical nor necessary for the external
targets as the calibrated rhodium-iron resistance thermometers were
inserted into thermowells and therefore mounted in a strain-free
condition.</p> <TABLE WIDTH=100% CELLPADDING="5%"><TR><TD VALIGN=TOP>
<CENTER>
<a href="blackbodies/fig3_large.jpg"><IMG
SRC="blackbodies/fig3_small.jpg"></a><BR> <BR><I>Fig 3: View of assembled enclosure</I></TD>
</CENTER>
</TD><TD>
<CENTER>
<a href="blackbodies/fig4_large.jpg"><IMG
SRC="blackbodies/fig4_small.jpg"></a><BR> <BR><I>Fig 4: View of targets undergoing integration and leak testing</I></TD>
</CENTER>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<p>The IFCBB was designed to be temperature stable over an orbital
period (approximately 100 minutes), to have a heater-controlled
set-point in the range 270 K to 320 K and to have redundant heaters
and sensors. The external calibration blackbodies were designed to be
temperature stable and uniform at radiometric calibration set-points
in the range <100 K to 320 K. The compact design was achieved through
the use of coaxial, cooled and heated cylindrical shields and
shrouds. Fast cooling rates were affected by an integral, helium gas
heat-switch, with the cooling power (helium partial pressure)
controlled by pumping and/or back-filling. The chosen cryogenic vacuum
seals ensured a high degree of hermeticity (low helium leakage rates),
even at chamber pressures 5.0 &times 10<sup><small>-7</small></sup>
mbar which were routinely achieved during instrument test and
calibration.</p>
